.TH CAPSULE 1 "2026-02-24" "capsule" "User Commands"
.
.SH NAME
capsule \- execute a command inside a Linux network namespace
.
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B capsule
.I netns
.I command
.RI [ args \&.\|.\|.]
.br
.B capsule list
.RB [ \-v ]
.br
.B capsule status
.RB [ \-v ]
.I netns
.
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B capsule
enters the network namespace identified by
.I netns
and executes
.I command
inside it.
It is designed to be installed with the
.B cap_sys_admin,cap_dac_read_search+ep
file capability (via
.BR setcap (8))
rather than as a setuid-root binary.
.PP
The sequence of operations is:
.IP 1. 3
Verify the caller is not root (UID\~0).
.IP 2.
Open
.I netns
and verify via
.BR fstatfs (2)
that it is a network namespace
.RB ( NSFS_MAGIC ).
.IP 3.
If
.IR /etc/netns/ name /resolv.conf
exists, create a private mount namespace and bind-mount it over
.IR /etc/resolv.conf
for DNS isolation.
.IP 4.
Call
.BR setns (2)
with
.B CLONE_NEWNET
to enter the namespace.
.IP 5.
Drop all capabilities (effective, permitted, inheritable, ambient) using
.BR libcap (3),
leaving the process fully unprivileged.
.IP 6.
Drop
.B cap_sys_admin
and
.B cap_dac_read_search
from the capability bounding set via
.BR prctl (2)
.BR PR_CAPBSET_DROP ,
preventing child processes from re-acquiring these capabilities through a
setcap binary.
.IP 7.
.BR execvp (3)
the requested command with the original UID/GID and the unmodified
environment.
.PP
Because
.B execvp
replaces the
.B capsule
process, the child's exit status is propagated directly to the caller.
.
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
.B list
List all named network namespaces found in
.IR /var/run/netns .
With
.BR \-v ,
also display the processes running inside each namespace.
Prints a message if the directory does not exist or is empty.
.
.TP
.B status
Show the network interfaces and running processes for a single namespace.
The
.I netns
argument accepts the same short name or full path as the exec form.
.B \-v
is accepted and reserved; status always shows full detail.
.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.I netns
Either a short namespace name or a full path.
If the argument contains no
.RB ' / ',
capsule constructs
.IR /var/run/netns/<name>
and uses that path.
Full paths (anything containing
.RB ' / ')
are used directly without modification, so
.IR /var/run/netns/vpn ,
.IR /proc/<pid>/ns/net ,
and similar paths all work as-is.
.
.TP
.I command
Name or path of the program to execute.
Searched via
.B PATH
if not an absolute path.
.
.TP
.RI [ args ]
Zero or more arguments forwarded verbatim to
.IR command .
.
.TP
.B \-v
Verbose mode.
For
.BR list :
show processes per namespace.
Accepted (and reserved) for
.BR status ,
which always shows full detail.
.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.B capsule
itself exits with status\~1 on any error before exec.
On success the exec form never returns — it becomes
.IR command ,
whose exit status is therefore the exit status seen by the caller.
The
.B list
and
.B status
subcommands exit 0 on success and 1 on error.
.
.SH ERRORS
Error messages are written to standard error with the prefix
.BR "capsule: " .
.
.TP
.B refusing to run as root (UID 0)
capsule was invoked by the root user.  Use
.BR "ip netns exec" (8)
or
.BR nsenter (1)
instead.
.
.TP
.IB netns-path ": No such file or directory"
The namespace file does not exist.
.
.TP
.IB netns-path ": not a network namespace"
The path exists but is not a namespace file
.RB ( fstatfs
did not return
.BR NSFS_MAGIC ).
.
.TP
.B setns(CLONE_NEWNET): \fR...
.BR setns (2)
failed.  Common causes: the file capability is missing
.RB ( cap_sys_admin
not set on the binary), or the namespace file is not readable.
.
.TP
.B cap_set_proc: failed to drop capabilities
.BR libcap (3)
could not clear the capability sets.
.
.TP
.IB command ": No such file or directory"
.I command
was not found on
.BR PATH .
.
.SH SECURITY
.SS File capabilities vs. setuid
capsule is installed with
.BR "setcap 'cap_sys_admin,cap_dac_read_search+ep'" ,
not as a setuid-root binary.  Two capabilities are used:
.TP
.B cap_dac_read_search
Open the network namespace file.
.BR "ip netns add" (8)
creates namespace files as bind mounts of nsfs inodes.
nsfs does not implement
.IR setattr ,
so
.BR chmod (1)
returns
.B EPERM
even for root — the files remain mode 000.
.B cap_dac_read_search
allows capsule to open them directly.
.TP
.B cap_sys_admin
Call
.BR setns (2)
to enter the network namespace.
.PP
Both capabilities are active only for the duration of the
.B capsule
process itself.  The child (after
.BR exec )
holds
.B no
capabilities.
.
.SS Capability drop
After
.BR setns ,
capsule calls
.BR cap_set_proc (3)
with an empty capability set, clearing the effective, permitted, and
inheritable sets.  Ambient capabilities are cleared via
.BR prctl (2)
.BR PR_CAP_AMBIENT_CLEAR_ALL .
The child therefore starts with the same privilege as any ordinary process
run directly by the user.
.PP
In addition, capsule drops
.B cap_sys_admin
and
.B cap_dac_read_search
from the capability bounding set via
.BR prctl (2)
.BR PR_CAPBSET_DROP .
Even though the effective/permitted/inheritable sets are already empty,
removing these from the bounding set prevents a child process that executes
a copy of capsule (or any other binary carrying the same file capabilities)
from re-acquiring
.B cap_sys_admin
or
.B cap_dac_read_search
and escaping the network namespace.
.
.SS Namespace file permissions
.B capsule
does not modify namespace file permissions.  The administrator is
responsible for granting read access to the namespace file
.RI ( chmod / chgrp )
for the users who should be allowed to enter it.  This is the access
control mechanism: if a user cannot open the file, they cannot enter the
namespace.
.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /var/run/netns/\fIname\fR
Conventional location for named network namespaces, managed by
.BR ip-netns (8).
.
.TP
.I /proc/\fIpid\fR/ns/net
Per-process network namespace file, readable if the caller has permission
to inspect the target process.
.
.SH EXAMPLES
Run Firefox inside a namespace named
.IR vpn
using the short name:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule vpn firefox
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Same using an explicit path:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule /var/run/netns/vpn firefox
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Open an interactive shell for debugging:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule vpn bash
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Check which external IP address is visible:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule vpn curl -s https://ifconfig.me
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Use the network namespace of a running process:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule /proc/1234/ns/net ip route show
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
List all named namespaces:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule list
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
List namespaces with their running processes:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule list -v
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Show interfaces and processes for a namespace:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule status vpn
.EE
.RE
.
.PP
Use a full path with status:
.PP
.RS
.EX
capsule status /proc/$$/ns/net
.EE
.RE
.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR ip-netns (8),
.BR nsenter (1),
.BR setns (2),
.BR setcap (8),
.BR getcap (8),
.BR cap_set_proc (3),
.BR capabilities (7),
.BR network_namespaces (7)
.
.SH AUTHOR
Written as a minimal capability-based namespace executor.
.
.SH CAVEATS
.IP \(bu 2
Only the network namespace is changed.  The mount, PID, UTS, IPC, and user
namespaces remain those of the calling process.
.IP \(bu
The child may lack capabilities it expects
.RB ( cap_net_raw ", " cap_net_bind_service ,
etc.).  Grant those via a separate
.BR setcap (8)
on the child binary if needed.
.IP \(bu
.B PR_CAP_AMBIENT_CLEAR_ALL
requires Linux\~4.3.  On older kernels the call is silently ignored.
